<TEXT>
the future is bleak for many children in 
americas cities unless the next president and congress make a 
commitment to solving some of their problems a massachusetts mayor 
said wednesday 
too many children in our cities have no future no future at 
all unless we as a nation act on the problems they face today 
said theodore d mann mayor of newton mass 
mann is chairman of the human development committee of the us 
conference of mayors which on wednesday released a status report 
on children in americas cities 
the report calls attention to our collective failure as a 
nation to respond to these problems mann said of the 52city 
survey of mayors and human service officials 
the study identifies drug abuse weaknesses in education systems 
the lack of affordable child care teenage pregnancy and school 
dropouts as key problems which have grown worse in the last five 
years in 80 percent of the cities surveyed 
officials said lowincome children are confronted with the 
additional problems of homelessness and the lack of access to 
medical and mental health care 
kevin moriarity director of human services for san antonio 
texas recounted some of the surveys gloomier statistics three of 
10 children in the cities surveyed lived in poverty in 1986 one in 
five was on welfare and received food stamps 38 percent dropped out 
of school between the ninth grade and their scheduled high school 
graduation in the class of 1988 15 percent of the babies born in 
1986 were born to teenage mothers and a 126 percent infant 
mortality rate plagued the cities during that year 
among survey cities irvine calif had the lowest overall 
poverty rate and child poverty rate in 1986 at 41 percent and 33 
percent respectively the city with the highest 1986 overall 
poverty rate and child poverty rate was camden nj at 423 
percent and 611 percent respectively 
meanwhile the urban institute released a study based on 1979 
data that showed that 171 percent of us children lived in 
families with income below the poverty level the poverty rate for 
children was 51 percent in sweden and switzerland and 82 percent 
in west germany 
the urban institute study said the high us poverty rate among 
children occurs because programs for the poor cover fewer people and 
provide fewer benefits than programs in other industrialized 
countries officials said the united states relative standing had 
changed little if any since 1979 
mann said the mayors conference was not interested in placing 
blame for the current problems but was calling for a national 
partnership between the business community and federal state and 
local governments 
however most speakers at wednesdays session of the us 
conference of city human service officials an affiliate of the 
mayors conference emphasized increasing the federal governments 
role both financially and in providing policy direction 
weve got to have more federal assistance not just in funding 
but in policy said james moran mayor of alexandria va 
we feel that we have done as much as we can and sometimes 
more moran said we are losing middleclass residents because 
of high property taxes used to pay for needed services he said 
moran said his community a prosperous suburb of washington 
faces a growing problem of homelessness fueled by a high dropout 
rate he cited an 186 percent dropout rate in 1987 among teenage 
girls due to pregnancy 
among the cities surveyed norfolk va had the highest dropout 
rate in the class of 1988 seventyone percent of norfolks 1988 
class left school from the ninth grade and 37 percent of the rest of 
those eligible for graduation in 1988 left in the tenth grade 
but george d raiss a spokesman for the norfolk public schools 
called the groups numbers completely erroneous 
the study did not take into account norfolks transient 
population the city is home to the worlds largest naval facility 
and the study counted as dropouts students who actually 
transferred from one school to another who transferred out of the 
district and those who were not promoted for academic reasons among 
others 
according to figures supplied to the state of virginia norfolk 
had a dropout rate of 81 percent in 1988 which was down from 91 
percent in 1987 and 158 percent in 1981 
the average wait for subsidized child care among surveyed cities 
was almost 10 months while the wait for nonsubsidized child care 
was 18 weeks with costs running an average of 78 weekly at a 
centerbased facility nationally half the children under 6 have 
mothers who work outside the home 
the group did not identify a specific amount they thought was 
needed from the federal government to address childrens problems 
but mann noted that both presidential candidates had emphasized 
childrens issues in their campaigns 
we need to hear more from each of them on a commitment of 
dollars we need to hear that they are willing to make the enormous 
investment that the problems demand and the children deserve 
mann added 
</TEXT>
