<TEXT>
two national polls have found george bush 
consolidating his lead in the presidential race with fewer voters 
saying they may change their minds although many remain 
dissatisfied with their choices 
bush held doubledigit leads in the cbs newsnew york times and 
gallup polls released tuesday further evidence of a surge for the 
republican nominee since his debate with democrat michael dukakis on 
oct 13 
bush led dukakis by 13 points among probable voters in the 
cbstimes poll 5441 percent and by 5040 among registered voters 
in gallups poll he led by 14 points among gallup respondents 
judged likely to vote 
bush had led by a consistent but narrow margin four to seven 
points in most polls since late august but the numbers started to 
move in his favor last week and the new results continued that 
trend 
in one key finding the cbstimes poll found clear success in 
bushs attacks on dukakis on crime sixtytwo percent said bush was 
tough enough in dealing with crime and criminals just 37 percent 
said the same of dukakis 
in another 25 percent said the political commercials they had 
seen helped them decide whom to support and more than half of that 
group went for bush still 62 percent said commercials had not 
helped them decide 
the polls found dissatisfaction with both nominees in the 
cbstimes poll 64 percent wished they had other choices than bush 
and dukakis and just 42 percent of gallups respondents had a 
strong preference compared with about 60 percent at this stage in 
the 1984 election 
the surveys nonetheless found voters more firm in their 
decisions in gallups 28 percent said they were undecided or could 
change their minds down from 37 percent before the debate in the 
cbstimes poll 74 percent said their minds were made up compared 
with 66 percent earlier 
as in other polls bush received disproportionate support from 
men they favored him by 54 percent to 38 percent in the gallup 
poll while women backed him by a far tighter 46 percent to 42 
percent margin 
the poll demonstrated that voter choices were based on the top of 
the ticket the democrats trailed even though dukakis running mate 
sen lloyd bentsen of texas was rated far more favorably than was 
bushs sen dan quayle of indiana bentsen was viewed favorably by 
59 percent unfavorably by 27 percent for quayle it was 4244 
fiftynine percent in the gallup poll said they had a favorable 
opinion of bush to 35 percent unfavorable dukakis did less well 
50 percent favorable 43 percent unfavorable the small remainders 
didnt answer 
the leads in the two polls were less than the bush advantage in 
the first fullsized survey conducted after the oct 13 debate an 
nbc newswall street journal poll that found him ahead by 17 points 
no other poll has found a bush lead that great it was followed 
by abc newswashington post and harris polls that found sizable but 
smaller bush leads seven and nine points respectively last 
weekend a newsweek poll done by gallup put the bush advantage at 
nine points 5041 
the new gallup poll released tuesday was conducted friday through 
sunday among 1232 registered voters and had margin of sampling 
error of plus or minus three points of the total 815 were 
considered to be likely voters the result among that group had a 
fourpoint error margin 
the cbstimes poll was conducted friday through monday among 
1287 probable voters and had a threepoint error margin 
meanwhile bush took a slight lead over dukakis in a statewide 
poll in rhode island which was long thought to be safe territory 
for the democrat from nearby massachusetts 
the poll conducted by joseph fleming amp associates for wpritv 
found bush with 46 percent support dukakis with 41 percent and 13 
percent not sure 
the survey of 414 registered voters was conducted last week and 
had a nearly fivepoint margin of error meaning the bush lead is 
just large enough to be statistically significant 
in the democratic stronghold of maryland bush led dukakis 51 
percent to 42 percent the washington post reported in todays 
editions the post survey of 601 likely voters was conducted tuesday 
through saturday and had a margin of error of four percentage points 
