<TEXT>
the operator of the contaminated three mile 
island nuclear plant hopes to mothball the reactor next year but a 
panel of citizens and scientists says more commitments to clean up 
the site are needed first 
a spokesman for the pennsylvania plants operator said tuesday 
that managers hoped to go ahead with the plan to place the crippled 
unit 2 reactor into monitored storage by the end of 1989 
next year will mark the 10th anniversary of the nations worst 
commercial nuclear accident at three mile island on march 31 1979 
the storage plan calls for the reactor building to be locked up 
and unneeded systems deactivated the plant would sit for perhaps 30 
years while radiation decays inside 
although the damaged nuclear fuel and loose radioactive 
components would have been removed from the plant radiation would 
remain in piping and other areas of the reactor building basement 
the advisory panel for the decontamination of unit 2 told the 
nuclear regulatory commission during a meeting tuesday that nine of 
its 11 members had sided against the socalled post defueling 
monitored storage plan which is known as pdms 
arthur e morris the panel chairman and the mayor of lancaster 
pa said many in the group felt the plan was too vague he said the 
panel believed the cleanup should proceed expeditiously 
with no specific funding in place morris said there were 
concerns that the cleanup of the plant might not be completed even 
after the storage phase ended in addition he said area residents 
were troubled by the uncertainty of not knowing exactly how many 
years the reactor would sit idle until it was decommissioned 
the utility seems to have looked at this pdms as a given and 
sort of expected us to go along with it said panel member joel 
roth 
in the 1979 accident unit 2 was allowed to lose vital cooling 
water that normally covers it the subsequent 1 billion cleanup has 
focused on water decontamination waste shipment and removal of fuel 
from the damaged core 
doug bedell a spokesman for gpu nuclear the plant operator 
said in an interview after tuesdays meeting that the cleanup would 
likely stop at the end of next year he said it was pointless to 
expose cleanup workers to additional risk after that because 
remaining radiation would be fixed in place presenting no 
threat to the public 
he said the utility envisioned letting unit 2 sit idle until 
after its twin unit 1 ended its service life in about the year 
2010 then both units would be dismantled together 
gpu nuclear would need an amendment to its nuclear regulatory 
commission license before it could proceed with its storage plan 
the decision on whether to grant the change would be made by the nrc 
staff although it is possible the commissioners themselves would 
get involved 
</TEXT>
