<TEXT>
president reagan has banned most nicaraguan 
government officials from entering the united states in the latest 
round of a titfortat diplomatic feud 
under a proclamation released tuesday by the white house reagan 
declared the unrestricted entry of officers and employees of 
the nicaraguan government and the sandinista national liberation 
front to be detrimental to the interests of the united states 
the prohibition applies to all nicaraguan government and party 
officials with the exception of those carrying out activities 
related to the united nations or other international organizations 
family members of such officials are exempted as well 
the diplomatic tussle began on july 11 when managua expelled 
us ambassador richard melton and seven other american officials on 
grounds they interfered in nicaraguas internal affairs 
the united states retaliated the next day by expelling nicaraguan 
ambassador carlos tunnermann and seven of his colleagues 
since then the sandinista government has not acted on us 
attempts to replace the expelled us envoys 
weve been trying to get our people replaced and we havent 
gotten anywhere white house spokesman roman popadiuk said 
a call placed to the nicaraguan embassy seeking comment was not 
returned 
the presidents action also comes in light of a new restriction 
placed on us officials in nicaragua last month 
on sept 22 the sandinista government imposed the new 
requirement that american diplomats based in nicaragua who leave the 
country for whatever reason must wait at least three weeks before 
they may return 
the dispute was aggravated last month when the reagan 
administration refused to allow nicaraguan president daniel ortega 
to bring a delegation of 60 nicaraguans on a proposed visit to the 
united nations and to washington 
the state department said the nicaraguans applied too late for 
their visas a claim the sandinistas denied ortega canceled the 
trip 
