<TEXT>
the national association of home builders says 
it wont recommend any changes in insulation practices to combat the 
buildup of radon which government officials say is probably the 
secondranking cause of lung cancer 
at a news conference tuesday an official with the association 
said it is telling its members to continue employing the same 
practices we have recommended for years for energy conservation 
john spears program manager at the associations national 
research center said weve found that energy conservation has 
little to do with radon concentration in the house 
spears conclusion tracks with our preliminary results over the 
past few years for both new homes and existing homes said 
environmental protection agency spokesman chris rice epa is engaged 
in a cooperative research program with the center 
but epa says increased ventilation still may be useful in 
reducing radon buildup in particular homes 
last month epa and the public health service advised that 
everyone living on a second floor or below should have indoor air 
tested for radon the public health service issued a health 
advisory elevating indoor radon to the same status as smoking as 
a health threat 
epa believes radon ranks second only to smoking as a cause of 
lung cancer of the 130000 annual deaths from lung cancer about 85 
percent are caused by smoking epa estimates radon could cause as 
many as 20000 deaths which if true would be roughly all those not 
caused by smoking 
radon is a radioactive gas emitted in some degree by all soils 
it quickly decays into other substances but its decay products are 
also radioactive and can lodge in the lung irradiating the tissue 
for a lifetime indoor dust and smoke and smoke from tobacco 
products can carry these decay products into the lung 
there are many techniques for reducing radon buildup often the 
same techniques that are used to keep water out of basements such as 
careful sealing of joints use of tight covers on sumps and a thick 
polyethylene barrier between the slab and the ground 
william h ethier litigation counsel for the association said 
members were being advised that if they make a reasoned judgment 
that there may be high radon levels they should rough in 
mitigation techniques such as underslab ventilation pipes that may 
be ignored later if appropriate or connected to a fan to divert 
radonladen air around the basement 
in states such as pennsylvania and new jersey with 
wellpublicized instances of radon buildup ethier said he has found 
universal adoption of such precautions by builders 
builders report that the techniques may add as little as 100 to 
the cost of a home if water barriers are already being used but as 
much as 600 if they are not he said 
</TEXT>
