<TEXT>
agriculture department scientists say that tiny 
beneficial worms or nematodes can be produced in a laboratory 
dried out for storage and revived later to fight destructive pests 
in back yards 
theyre still living and breathing but theyre dormant says 
entomologist james e lindegran of the departments agricultural 
research service laboratory fresno calif 
lindegran and researchers at a california biotechnology firm 
biosys found that the microscopic nematodes such as steinernema 
feltiae can be dried stored as a paste under refrigeration and 
then revived with water 
when you add water the worms plump back up again lindegran 
said in a report issued here by the usda agency when they start 
moving around theyre ready to be sprayed onto plants trees or 
soil 
the beneficial nematodes attack pests that are in the larvaal or 
wormlike stage of development by entering through openings such as 
the mouth or breathing tubes he said 
once inside a pest the nematodes excrete a unique bacterium 
that kills the pest is food for the nematodes and produces 
antibiotics that keep other bacteria at bay lindegran said 
the nematodes are harmless to humans but lethal to a variety of 
pests including carpenterworms cutworms armyworms fruit flies 
and root maggots 
</TEXT>
