doctors and nurses face a oneinathousand 
risk of catching aids when they get infected blood or other body 
fluids on their skin even though gloves they wear for protection 
often leak studies found 
gloves have been leaking for years weve been wearing them and 
we havent found a lot of infections in hospital employees exposed 
to aids hepatitis b and other viruses said jane 
degrootkosolcharoen an infection control nurse at middleton 
memorial veterans hospital in madison wis 
three studies conducted by degrootkosolcharoen and researchers 
in massachusetts and florida found leakage in more than half of some 
of the brands of gloves tested one study was conducted as an 
eighthgrade science project by a student whose father is an 
infectious disease expert 
the studies found wide variations in leakage rates for various 
brands of latex and vinyl gloves but tended to show sterile 
surgical gloves less leakprone than nonsterile examination gloves 
and latex less leakprone than vinyl 
a fourth study concluded blood sputum urine and other body 
fluids of aids patients gets on the skin of health care workers 
far too frequently with about onequarter of a group of 770 
hospital employees getting aidstainted liquids on their skin 
but the chance of one such exposure infecting a person with the 
virus for acquired immune deficiency syndrome is no more than 11 in 
