<TEXT>
atlantic salmon are swimming in the 
shetucket river for the first time in about 150 years 
state department of environmental protection workers on tuesday 
released some 200 salmon as part of a program aimed at reintroducing 
the oncenative fish into the thames river and its tributaries 
atlantic salmon were once plentiful in the rivers of southeastern 
connecticut powergeneration dams along the rivers first installed 
in the mid1800s prevented the salmon from swimming to their 
spawning grounds 
the effort to reintroduce the fish if successful would be not 
only a victory for conservationists but also a boon for the local 
economy as fishermen journey to the region for the chance to catch 
the prized fish 
when oswego county in new york reintroduced salmon into its 
rivers early this decade tourists pumped an additional 7 million 
to 8 million into the economy annually according to studies 
ronald r whiteley president of the thames river watershed 
association said some of the salmon probably will begin migrating 
down the thames on a 6000mile trip to the waters of greenland and 
back 
the earliest the fish would return would be 1990 by then 
whiteley said it is hoped a fish ladder at greeneville dam will be 
completed to allow the fish to continue upstream to natural spawning 
grounds in shallow waters 
however the restocking effort will not succeed until fish 
ladders are installed at two dams farther north it could take 
decades for the river to become a natural habitat again for the 
salmon whiteley said 
but tuesday was a start the fish were trucked to the banks of 
the river then unloaded by net into large plastic barrels workers 
carried the barrels to the waters edge and dumped the fish into the 
river the salmon are identified with yellow tags attached to a fin 
the fish about two to three pounds apiece were raised in the 
kensington state salmon hatchery in berlin 
</TEXT>
