<TEXT>
as his underdog campaign draws to a close 
democratic nominee michael dukakis is leaning on his partys 
traditional populist themes that put harry truman over the top in 
1948 and shifted millions of votes to hubert humphrey in 1968 
the massachusetts governor has touted his competence hes 
boasted about his good judgment in selecting lloyd bentsen as his 
vice presidential running mate hes attacked ethical lapses in the 
reagan administration and hes derided republican rival george bush 
as the artificial creation of cynical handlers 
but with his growing deficit in the polls and the increasing 
impatience of his supporters dukakis is finally homing in on a 
classoriented easy street vs main street message that has served 
democrats well in the past 
the real question is will we have a president who fights for 
the privileged few or will we have a president who fights for 
you he asks in a late october campaign advertisement typical of 
his new approach 
george bush wants to give the wealthiest 1 percent of the 
people in this country a new tax break worth 30000 a year he 
says im fighting for you and your family for affordable housing 
and health care for better jobs for the best education and 
opportunity for our children 
democratic consultants with long memories can hardly conceal 
their elation they say theyve been urging dukakis to take this 
tack for months 
theres now been a shift to distinguishing what really makes 
the democrats distinctive and different we care about the average 
person we believe government can have a constructive role in 
helping the average person says stuart eizenstat an unofficial 
adviser to the dukakis campaign who formerly worked for humphrey and 
president carter 
its very important for a democratic candidate to remind people 
who does what for them says adviser robert hunter a foreign 
affairs specialist and a former humphrey speechwriter 
the governor is catching up with the kind of strategy that can 
work for him and lets hope better late than never pays off 
hunter said 
twenty years ago with humphrey lagging 15 points behind richard 
nixon three weeks before the 1968 election pollster vic fingerhut 
wrote a memo that resonates eerily in 1988 
fingerhuts advice to the humphrey campaign concentrate on 
voters likely to cross party lines george wallace and nixon 
democrats in 1968 reagan democrats in 1988 reach them with short 
tv ads stress economic themes raise the specters of education and 
social spending cutbacks and hammer home the idea that humphrey is 
a tough fighter for the common man 
the memo cited findings that truman won late votes because of 
economic concerns not because he was a feisty underdog people 
came to vote for truman faster than they came to like him 
fingerhut wrote 
his conclusion forget about trying to make humphrey likable and 
go back to democratic roots 
according to fingerhut 8 million votes shifted to the vice 
president in the final three weeks before the 1968 election most of 
them bluecollar and middleclass voters with socially conservative 
attitudes the same kinds of people dukakis needs to attract 
fingerhut attributes 7 million of those votes to economic 
concerns others such as eizenstat say part of the late rally was 
promoted by humphreys declaration of independence from president 
johnson on the vietnam war but they say economic issues were at 
least equally important 
the dukakis camp their candidate more comfortable as a 
cleangovernment crusader than a class warrior auditioned other 
messages for weeks 
they tried real hard to reinvent the wheel and when they ended 
up it wasnt even round said dan payne a boston advertising 
executive who did primary spots for dukakis 
now in his speeches and commercials dukakis talks of day care 
family leave education jobs trade home ownership health care 
and the struggles of twoearner families to keep up 
hes on their side he says of bush and the wealthy im on 
your side 
will wavering democrats and independents respond to this late 
populist appeal 
eizenstat said those issues proved potent for humphrey in the 
face of a nixon assault that included the same charges of weak on 
defense and soft on crime that bush is using against dukakis 
now that people are really focused on the 1988 campaign they 
will respond to the very same breadandbutter issues eizenstat 
said 
dukakis has a few problems that humphrey didnt have the 
democratic majority of registered voters is smaller than it was in 
1968 and party ties are weaker humphrey was part of a democratic 
administration while dukakis is a nonwashington candidate who must 
convince voters that the white house needs a change of party 
humphrey was further behind than dukakis in the final stretch of 
the campaign though his momentum by election day led many to 
believe that humphrey could have beaten nixon in a few more days 
the humphrey and truman models should be the dukakis model 
says fingerhut if he follows those models he can win the 
election 
</TEXT>
