<TEXT>
the government should step up research and 
promotion of socalled lowinput farming to halt contamination of 
groundwater with nitrates and pesticides a house panel said 
wednesday 
given the seriousness of the problems besetting agriculture 
today the least we can do is ensure that this option is available 
for farmers said rep mike synar dokla chairman of the 
environment energy and natural resources subcommittee 
the panel released a report based on a yearlong investigation of 
the pesticide issue low input farming systems benefits and 
barriers 
lowinput farming refers to techniques ranging from 
chemicalfree or organic agriculture to the careful targeting 
and reduced use of chemical pesticides on crops 
the epa estimates that of 11 billion pounds of pesticides used 
in the united states in 1984 77 percent or 861 million pounds 
were applied to agricultural crops 
these chemicals some of which have been linked to cancer and 
other health problems along with nitrates from agricultural 
fertilizers have increasingly been found in groundwater which 
furnishes the major drinking supply to almost half of all americans 
while a lowinput management system is not a cureall for 
agricultures troubles it offers the potential of improving the 
efficiency of farm operations by lowering input costs and reducing 
contaminants that end up in the soil and groundwater synar said 
the panel reported that even when cutting back on pesticides had 
reduced crop yield some farmers reported greater net earnings 
because of reduced production costs 
but the epa has focused little attention on nonchemical methods 
in reaching its regulatory decisions the report said poor 
coordination between the agency and the agriculture department are 
to blame it said 
the panel also cited an array of barriers to widespread adoption 
of lowinput methods to us farming they included lack of 
research chemical industry influence on farmers limited 
information available and worry among agricultural producers that 
switching to alternative production methods would risk shortterm 
income loss 
in 1985 the report said congress authorized the agriculture 
department to develop a lowinput farming methods program it said 
however that the department did not request money for it and that 
it remained unfunded until lawmakers approved 41 million in the 
fiscal year that ended last month 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

