about 30 to their 60s listened to the late 1960searly 1970s medley 
with serious expressions and varied postures one middleaged man 
yawned at one point while several jurors nodded in time to the beat 
the defense witness harold barlow who described himself as a 
music plagiarism expert as well as a songwriter and arranger 
said all the songs had many notes in common 
he fogerty is working with an idea barlow said the idea 
is to use bflat and c in a repetitive structure mr fogerty 
has made this structure commonplace the way he uses them the 
expression of the idea theyre used differently 
under crossexamination barlow acknowledged that he had compared 
the two songs early in the case without examining any other songs 
and concluded they were substantially similar the standard that 
determines copyright infringement 
but he insisted that a valid comparison must also take into 
account earlier works that might have influenced later compositions 
in light of those old man down the road cant be considered a 
copy of the 1970 song barlow said 
