<TEXT>
for bush and dukakis the 1988 campaign was a political roller 
coaster 
the vice president started out facing demands that he separate 
himself from reagan and establish his own identity 
economic hard times in the midwest and the irancontra scandal 
were considered formidable obstacles in bushs path to the white 
house 
the first major test in the fight for the republican presidential 
nomination the iowa precinct caucuses bore that out when bush 
finished an embarrassing third behind senate gop leader bob dole and 
television evangelist pat robertson 
but a funny thing happened on the way to bushs political 
funeral he bounced back to win the new hampshire primary after 
suffering two more midwest defeats in south dakota and minnesota 
bush effectively closed out the gop race on super tuesday when he 
won all 16 primaries most of them in the south 
dukakis had a longer road he finished a respectable third in 
iowa and then won new hampshire and established his frontrunner 
status on super tuesday but poor showings in illinois and michigan 
kept the race open 
in the spring dukakis found his stride and reeled off a series 
of primary victories that narrowed the field to himself and jesse 
jackson week after week dukakis beat jackson and also saw national 
polls giving him a strong lead over bush 
by the end of the democratic national convention in july polls 
said dukakis was favored over bush by a margin of up to 17 points 
his choice of texas sen lloyd bentsen as a running mate was 
widely applauded and was regarded as a direct challenge to bush in 
his adopted home state the third biggest electoral prize 
a month later it was bushs turn in contrast to dukakis choice 
of bentsen the bush selection of sen dan quayle of indiana was 
widely criticized 
the rival candidates used almost identical words to state their 
overall goal 
i seek the presidency to build a better america its that 
simple said bush 
i want to be president not because its the next rung on the 
ladder but because its the way to act on my values and build the 
best america said dukakis 
but the campaign rhetoric didnt remain that lofty 
the democratic nominee was strangely silent during the summer 
while the bush campaign unleashed a strong campaign focusing on 
dukakis veto of legislation requiring recitation of the pledge of 
allegiance his states prison furlough program and pollution in 
boston harbor 
not until the final weeks of the campaign when polls had shifted 
from the impressive dukakis lead to a steady margin for bush did 
the democratic nominee start striking back 
not only did dukakis finally respond to the bush attacks but he 
also began sounding a new and sharper populist message 
george bush wants to help the people who already have it 
made he told large enthusiastic crowds i want to help every 
american family make it 
bush was closing out his campaign by staying with the pattern 
that had worked so well to date days that usually began with an 
issues speech and by afternoon shifted to standard stump rhetoric 
including the attacks on dukakis as soft on crime and defense and as 
an unrepentant liberal 
