<TEXT>
from gun control in maryland to a smoking ban in oregon and tax 
cuts in south dakota utah and colorado 234 ballot issues will be 
decided by voters in 41 states on election day 
california birthplace a decade ago of a voterdriven tax revolt 
that quickly spread to many other states has two of the nations 
most closely watched contests 
californians will choose among five separate ballot measures 
reducing automobile insurance premiums insurers fearing a 
nationwide insurance revolt are spending more than 40 million 
in an attempt to defeat the proposals 
the fear is that some of the worst parts of the initiatives 
would eventually find their way into the thinking of insurance 
regulators across the country even in states which dont allow 
voter initiatives said herbert goodfriend an insurance industry 
analyst for prudentialbache securities 
also controversial is california proposition 102 which would 
eliminate the statewide anonymous aids testing program allow 
insurers and employers to screen prospective clients and workers 
and require health officials to do everything reasonably 
necessary to halt the epidemic including tracing the contacts of 
anyone exposed to the aids virus 
the chief sponsor is paul gann the tax crusader who helped 
spearhead property taxslashing proposition 13 a decade ago and who 
is now suffering from acquired immune deficiency syndrome because of 
a tainted blood transfusion 
among other ballot contests 
maryland voters will decide whether to keep a law passed this 
spring designed to ban cheap handguns known as saturday night 
specials the national rifle association has pumped 3 million into 
the repeal effort 
oregonians will vote on whether to toughen the oregon indoor 
clean air act which was passed in 1981 and bans smoking in most 
public buildings the new proposal would wipe out designated smoking 
areas and impose an outright ban on smoking in virtually all indoor 
work areas and enclosed public places 
californians meanwhile will consider a proposal to raise 
cigarette taxes by 25 cents a pack using proceeds to promote health 
in new york gov mario cuomo is pushing a 3 billion 
transportation bond issue the biggest borrowing in state history 
to fix roads and bridges opponents challenge the wisdom of such a 
huge borrowing for that purpose 
south dakota utah and colorado voters will decide measures that 
would reduce various taxes 
dakota proposition ii would roll back property taxes on 
agricultural property to 1 percent of 1984 values and 25 percent 
on nonagricultural property in stages by 1991 it would limit 
increases in property valuations to 2 percent a year local 
governments could impose special taxes if twothirds of the voters 
approve 
colorados socalled taxpayers bill of rights amendment would 
require voters to decide all future tax increases except in 
emergencies cut the income tax by about 10 percent and limit 
residential property taxes to 1 percent of market value 
utah voters face three tax initiatives that together would reduce 
state and local revenues by 329 million one would limit property 
taxes a second would roll back 1987 tax increases on income sales 
gasoline and cigarettes and a third would give tax credits for 
private education 
in michigan pro and antiabortion forces are waging 
multimillion dollar campaigns over a ballot measure that would 
outlaw statefunded abortions for the poor 
arkansas voters will decide whether to enshrine its existing 
noabortion spending policy in the state constitution while 
coloradans will get the chance to repeal a similar constitutional 
provision 
idaho indiana kentucky and minnesota have lottery questions on 
the nov 8 ballot and polls indicate support for those issues 
south dakotans will decide whether to clear the way for legalized 
gambling in the black hills town of deadwood where wild bill hickok 
was gunned down while playing poker 112 years ago town officials 
want to bring back gambling to help them raise money to preserve 
historic buildings 
under a rallying cry of personal freedom montana voters will 
consider whether to repeal its yearold seat belt law massachusetts 
and nebraska voters have previously done so 
utilities are waging a 5 million campaign in massachusetts to 
defeat a measure that could lead to the nations first 
votermandated closure of a nuclear power plant 
among local ballot contests boston residents will decide whether 
to permit predominantly black neighborhoods to become a separate new 
city named mandela after the south african black nationalist nelson 
mandela 
and the college enclaves of cambridge mass and berkeley 
calif have similar referendums demanding that israel end its 
violations of palestinian human rights and its occupation of the 
west bank and gaza 
commented harvard law school professor alan dershowitz only 
cambridge and berkeley would have the chutzpah to think that they 
can determine national and international policy by a local ballot on 
as complicated an issue 
</TEXT>
