<TEXT>
employment costs have risen faster than 
inflation over the past 12 months but largely because of soaring 
benefit costs primarily from higher social security taxes rather 
than wage gains according to new government data 
wages in the 12 months ended oct 1 rose an average of 39 
percent the labor department said tuesday compared with a 42 
percent increase in consumer prices over the same period 
but benefit costs have soared more than 67 percent more than 
double the 31 percent gain during the previous 12 months the 
departments bureau of labor statistics said 
the combined effect of the pay raises and higher benefit costs 
sent total employer costs up 47 percent in the 12 months ended oct 
1 compared with a 34 percent rise in the previous 12month period 
it said 
the steep increase in benefit costs resulted primarily from a 
rise last january in employers social security tax rate from 715 
percent to 751 percent the government said 
but there also were large increases in health insurance costs the 
first nine months of this year it noted and for the first time 
the government is calculating lumpsum bonus payments from union 
contracts and profitsharing arrangements as a benefit 
previously those bonuses had not been included as either wages or 
benefits 
nonunion employees continued to get bigger percentage pay raises 
than union members a trend begun in 1983 except for bluecollar 
workers in manufacturing 
the labor department said wage rates among union members rose an 
average 29 percent in the past 12 months compared with 39 percent 
for nonunion workers in the previous 12month period union wages 
rose an average 17 percent compared with 38 percent for nonunion 
employees 
this pattern reversed when limited to bluecollar workers in 
manufacturing the bureau said with wage increases in the past 
year averaging 32 percent for union members and 28 percent for 
nonunion workers 
including the lumpsum bonus arrangements that have become a norm 
in many labor contracts especially in manufacturing total employer 
compensation costs have risen the same 45 percent for union and 
nonunion workers nationwide the bureau said 
john zalusky an economist for the aflcio called the statistics 
refreshing 
we expected they were in that range zalusky said theyre 
the government beginning to show in fact what is really going on 
out there in the world but there still is a good way to go 
for example zalusky cited the last round of steel industry 
contracts in which the union conceded pay cuts to companies then 
operating at losses in exchange for a share of future profits or 
stock transfers if no profits occurred 
the statistics are now picking up the profit distributions but 
not the stock transfers for what essentially is a debt owed 
workers he said in the future i expect them to start putting 
in the value of stock ownership plans and in the distant future 
retraining funds such as those negotiated with the auto companies 
despite the disparity in percentage wage increases in recent 
years union workers continue to make 35 percent more than nonunion 
workers an average gap of 123 a week in 1987 compared with a gap 
of 119 in 1986 on a nationwide basis according to government 
data 
among whitecollar workers wage increases averaged 42 percent 
over the past 12 months compared with 4 percent the previous 12 
months the government said bluecollar wages have increased 33 
percent and 26 percent respectively over the same two periods 
the biggest pay gains 56 percent on average were among 
business and health service workers followed by average increases 
of 49 percent for professional and technical employees 
managers and executives along with state and local government 
workers have averaged the same 47 percent wage gains over the past 
year the average pay increase among private industry workers was 
37 percent 
by regions the biggest pay increases over the past 12 months 
have been in the northeast 46 percent followed by the south at 
38 percent average raises in the west and midwest were 32 percent 
and 29 percent respectively 
in a separate report the labor department said annual pay rose 
an average 46 percent among the 101 million workers with jobs in 
the nations 317 metropolitan areas last year 
kenosha wis with large pay increases in manufacturing and 
construction had the biggest average increase up 106 percent 
from 18666 in 1986 to 20648 in 1987 
the new havenwaterburymeriden area of connecticut and the 
monmouthocean city nj metropolitan areas were next with average 
annual pay increases of 84 percent last year 
on the other end of the scale workers in flint mich with a 
large decline in employment and falling wages in manufacturing 
suffered an average pay loss of 42 percent from 26633 in 1986 
to 25514 last year 
other cities where average pay fell last year were anchorage 
alaska anderson ind enid okla lawrence kan lansing mich 
