<DOCNO> AP881026-0264 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
four out of 10 americans covered by health 
insurance have encountered some form of insurance fraud including 
being billed for unnecessary tests or for medical services they 
never received according to a national survey commissioned by an 
insurance company 
the survey which is to be released formally on thursday was 
conducted for aetna life amp casualty which estimates that health 
care insurance fraud is responsible for about 10 percent of the 555 
billion americans spend on health care each year 
the survey indicates that there is widespread public awareness 
more than we thought that health insurance fraud is hurting 
consumers james l garcia director of fraud investigations in 
aetnas employee benefits division said wednesday in an interview 
garcia said consumers end up paying higher premiums to cover the 
cost of fraud 
however the survey found that the most widespread form of health 
care insurance fraud is one that few consumers complain about 
twentythree percent of the respondents said their practitioners 
had accepted insurance reimbursement as full payment even though 
their policies required the patient to pay a portion of the bill 
three out of five people required to pay a portion of their 
medical bills said they would consider switching to a doctor who 
practices that form of fraud 
to us that was an astonishing figure garcia said 
he said the study indicated that practitioners who would alter 
bills in that fashion were likely to practice other forms of fraud 
such as billing for unnecessary tests or services not provided 
ten percent of the survey respondents said they had been billed 
for laboratory tests they felt were unnecessary and 6 percent said 
their practitioners had inflated charges 
other forms of fraud cited were billing for services not rendered 
and charging more for services than had been discussed with the 
patient 
sixty percent of those responding to the survey said they had no 
experience with fraudulent tactics 
garcia said the study contained both good and bad news for 
insurance companies on the positive side consumers seemed very 
aware of the terms of their policies and often made an effort to 
examine their bills 
however consumers were also likely to turn to practitioners when 
they had doubts about their bills he said 
thats like being kidnapped and then asking the person who 
kidnapped you whether he really meant it garcia said 
to counter that garcia said aetna plans to introduce a fraud hot 
line 
were going to try to make it as easy as possible for consumers 
to notify the insurance agency he said 
the survey found that consumers consider healthcare insurance 
fraud among the most serious forms of whitecollar crime only stock 
market insider trading was considered more severe 
and a majority of the respondents 55 percent said practitioners 
found guilty of fraud should have their licenses either suspended or 
revoked 
however respondents to the survey ranked healthcare insurance 
fraud fifth when they were asked why medical costs and insurance 
premiums have risen over the last several years 
eightyfour percent of those responding said they thought 
malpractice suits and the cost of malpractice insurance were 
responsible for the increased costs and 53 percent blamed insurance 
companies for causing the increases by seeking to increase their own 
profits 
the cost of new technology and general inflation were both cited 
by 51 percent followed by health care insurance fraud blamed by 47 
percent of the respondents 
national family opinion conducted the survey for aetna by mailing 
a fourpage questionnaire to 1000 households in august a total of 
705 people responded giving the survey a margin of error of plus or 
minus 5 percent 
of those who responded 91 percent said they had some form of 
health insurance and 24 percent said they were covered by medicare 
of medicaid 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

