<TEXT>
the proposed 22 billion merger between 
pacificorp and utah power amp light was approved wednesday by the 
federal energy regulatory commission but only on the condition that 
the new company provide space on its transmission lines for other 
utilities to ship electricity 
in a 70page order the commission said requirements that the 
merged company wheel electricity from other utilities were aimed 
at alleviating fears it would dominate the sale of power from the 
inland northwest to the southwest 
we believe that the conditions are the minimum necessary to 
alleviate these likely anticompetitive effects so as to make the 
merger consistent with the public interest the commission said 
the merger would create the nations 13th largest utility serving 
more than 12 million customers in seven western states 
california washington oregon montana idaho wyoming and utah 
the commissions handling of the case has been closely watched by 
the utility industry which has been swept by talk over the last 
several years of deregulation and increased competition 
the commission in its order asserted its right to condition a 
merger so that it would be consistent with the public interest 
and found that without imposing conditions in this case the merger 
would enhance the ability of the new company to exercise 
monopoly power 
the commission ordered that in the shortterm the new company 
must set aside a portion of its transmission line capacity for 
others to use 
in the longterm the commission said the new company had an 
absolute obligation to provide transmission service to any 
utility that makes a bona fide request even if that means the 
company has to build new transmission facilities 
the directors of both pacificorp and utah power are expected to 
meet early next week to decide whether to proceed with the proposed 
merger the companies have 60 days to notify ferc of their decision 
or they can request a rehearing 
we need to satisfy ourselves that conditions imposed on the 
merged company will not materially impair our ability to acheive the 
customer and shareholder benefits we expect as a result of the 
combination david bolander president of pacificorps utility 
subsidiary pacific power amp light said in a statement 
patrick slattery a pacific power spokesman said that the 
company was somewhat surprised by the conditions imposed by the 
commission 
they appear to be unlike anything we have seen before said 
slattery it will take some time to get a firm grip on what the 
implications are 
shareholders of pacificorp based in portland ore and utah 
power based in salt lake city along with regulatory agencies in 
each of the states and the department of justice and federal trade 
commission have raised no objections to the merger 
but almost two dozen public and private utilities and utility 
organizations stretching from arizona to south dakota opposed the 
merger fearing it would create a megautility that would dominate 
western energy markets 
in june a ferc administrative law judge had recommended 
rejection of the proposed merger because of the impact it might have 
on utility competition 
pacificorp and utah power officials have said the merger could 
result in annual savings of up to 150 million over the first five 
years stable rates for pacific power customers and a drop in rates 
of up to 10 percent for utah power customers 
pacific power and light currently serves about 670000 customers 
in oregon washington california montana idaho and wyoming 
utah power has about 510000 customers in utah wyoming and idaho 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

