<TEXT>
sb fuller known as the dean of black 
entrepreneurs after he built a doortodoor cosmetics company into a 
national company with more than 5000 salesmen has died at age 83 
fuller died monday of kidney failure in st francis hospital in 
suburban blue island 
sb fullers success and his personal precept that an 
individual could achieve financial independence through 
selfdirection and hard work greatly influenced the chicago minority 
business scene in the 1940s and 1950s said gwynne goodlet a 
fuller products co spokesman 
at its peak in the 1960s fuller products co included 
newspapers appliance outlets and department stores as well as 
farming and cattle interests 
fuller who was unrelated to fuller brush company founder alfred 
c fuller was the first black member of the national association of 
manufacturers he also trained other black business people 
including magazine publishers john h johnson and mary ellen schadd 
strong and cosmetics magnate george johnson 
a native of louisiana fuller left school after the sixth grade 
his mother who died when he was 17 convinced him that the best way 
out of poverty was doortodoor sales 
after hitchhiking to chicago he became a salesman for the 
commonwealth burial association insurance co by 1934 he had become 
its manager 
in 1935 he started fuller products with 25 borrowed on his car 
and then used doortodoor sales representatives to handle 30 items 
from a littleknown cosmetics line 
fuller products peaked in the 1960s with sales of 10 million 
annually and sales offices in 38 states the company lost business 
the 1960s however to boycotts by white supremecists and also by 
blacks who objected to a fuller statement that a lack of 
understanding of the capitalist system and not racial barriers was 
keeping blacks from making progress 
fuller brought the company through a bankruptcy reorganization in 
1971 and reported a profit of 300000 in 1972 
fuller is survived by his wife lestine and five daughters 
burial services were scheduled friday in chicago 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

